			<p>In a game where bodies flew and landed painfully on the wooden court, the Concordia Stingers women’s basketball team could have made a case for their fifth straight win, a 67-54 trouncing of the <span class="caps">UQAM</span> Citadins on Friday, to be registered in another sport according to team head coach Keith Pruden. </p>
			
			
			
				

				
					<p>“The idea is to play basketball, not rugby,” Pruden said after the win, citing the Citadins’ physical aggressiveness. </p>

